Permissions - VPC SC rules
Introduction
Apart from attaching an access level to a rule, the content of the rule itself will allow to limit user permission on a scope of ressources (projects) and permissions. See for instance this sample: https://gitlab.richemont.com/scm_project/ric/dataplatforms_datalake/dataplatform_vpc_sc_exception/-/blob/main/rule_group_example/gcp-dl-dataops-engineers@richemont.com_egress.yml



# ======================================================================
# USE CASE DESCRIPTION
# - Describe why this access is necessary to ease approval by GroupSec 
# ======================================================================
# egress for gcp-dl-dataops-engineers@richemont.com
from:
  identities:
    - group:gcp-dl-dataops-engineers@richemont.com
  sources:
    - accessLevel: accessPolicies/id/accessLevels/name1
    - accessLevel: accessPolicies/id/accessLevels/name2
to:
  operations:
    - service_name: bigquery.googleapis.com
      permission_selectors:
      - bigquery.datasets.create
      - bigquery.tables.create
      - bigquery.tables.update
      - bigquery.tables.updateData
  resources:
    - projects/362100686259 # ric-eu-dl-ops-dev-nprd
 

Scenario 1: permissive version
In this version, the idea would be to apply restriction only at source IP level, IE, apart from accessLevel described in section #### the operations and ressources would be wildcard such as:



from:
  identities:
    - *
  sources:
    - accessLevel: accessPolicies/id/accessLevels/SipaAccess
to:
  operations:
    - "*"
  resources:
    - "*"
Pros
No need to define and maintain a complex mapping of users → groups → group permissions

No complex interaction between IAM and VPC-SC, ie both feature become independant from each other

Same rule across ALL perimeters (50+ perimeters in all richemont)

Cons
Access restriction solely relies on network, ie use of zscaler

 

